<section xml:id="section-assignment-week8">
  <title>Week 8 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the determinants of the following matrices using
        cofactor expansion. Show the steps of the algorithm clearly.
        (16). 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            7 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\
            -4 \amp -1 \amp -4 \\
            0 \amp 6 \amp 9
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 \amp -9 \amp -9 \\
            2 \amp -3 \amp -3 \\
            4 \amp -7 \amp -7
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 \amp -396 \amp 212 \\
            0 \amp 4 \amp -716 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Under what conditions for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the
        following matrices invertible? (6) 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
            b \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp a \amp a \\
            0 \amp b \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp b 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Using the definition and properties of the determinant from
        the video and the notes, prove the following statements.
        Assume, throughout, that <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times
        n </m> matrices. (Some of these are just one or two lines,
        connecting the relevant properties from different sections of
        the notes. Others are short calculations using the properties.
        Don't expect any of these to be long arguments.)
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          If <m>\Ker A = \{0\}</m>, then <m>\det A \neq 0</m>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          If <m>A</m> has more than <m>n^2 - n</m> entries which are
          o, then <m>\det A = 0</m>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <m>\det (AA^T)</m> can't be negative. 
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          If <m>A</m> is invertible, then <m>\det (ABA^{-1}) = \det
          B</m>. 
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <m>A^{-1}</m> cannot have a row of zeroes. 
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
